surprising , as anyone with both the imaginative capacity and sufficient powers of introspection to do so should potentially be able to notice the characteristic nature of vital metaphors and develop their own understanding of them, and again the fact that Stern uses the term 'vital' to describe them also falls out of similar lines of reasoning; to capture the sense of how they relate to the 'aliveness' as opposed to the 'deadness' of other metaphorical expressions used in everyday speach and express this in a more nuanced way then by simply calling them 'living'.}
\par \pard\plain \s0{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\nowidctlpar\cf0\kerning1\hich\af3\langfe2052\dbch\af3\afs24\lang1081\loch\f3\fs24\lang3081\sl276\slmult1\sb0\sa200{\afs22\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs22\lang9
Having said that, his description differs from mine in a number of ways, but rather then being contradictory to my account, his work seems to describe additional features of the Vitalistic Imagination that I had not been able to, but which complement my own work. Conversely, it also seems to be the case that my descriptions cover aspects of it that Stern's do not, though there is still a core that both our accounts share. One key feature which Stern's approach lacks, though this shouldn't be surprising in the slightest, is that while he provides a treatment of vital metaphors, he doesn't recognise anything like Vitalistic Imagination as a specific, discrete imaginatory capacity upon which they rely. Of course, he is unlikely to have any reason to, as anyone having not undergone the same transition I have consiously, while being in a position to analyse it in the way I did, would have no reason to suspect that a capacity of such a nature would actualy underly it. So, naturally, rather then this being a negative, if anything it only ought to futher support my ideas by providing an independent account of them, showing that the experience of the vitalistic is distinct enough to introspection that others can notice it as well. Another aspect that I focus on, but which isn't covered in what I have read of Stern to the same extent, is what might be termed a qualia-based phenomonological account of the expereince of vital metaphor, a sense of }{\i\afs22\ai\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs22\lang9
what it is like}{\afs22\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs22\lang9
 to experience it as opposed to other kinds of experience, similarly to how one might attempt to describe the specific qualities of sight to a person blind from birth, despite the difficulties of actually doing so, so that if he eventually does come to see, he might be able to understand that one aspect of what has come into his perception is what we call color. Of course, if Stern doesn't recognize vital metaphor, and VI, as something which can be completely absent from a person's consious experience prior to becomming active, and furthermore possibly has no recollection of a time when this might have been the case for him, then it's understandable that he would not think to write to much about it from such a perspective. Even so, he does hint at a number of distinct qualities for it, and he specifically gives a much more in depth treatment of the structural qualities he percieves it to have, which I want to highlight later.}
\par \pard\plain \s0{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\nowidctlpar\cf0\kerning1\hich\af3\langfe2052\dbch\af3\afs24\lang1081\loch\f3\fs24\lang3081\sl276\slmult1\sb0\sa200{\afs22\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs22\lang9
