\par \pard\plain \s0{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\nowidctlpar\cf0\kerning1\hich\af3\langfe2052\dbch\af3\afs24\lang1081\loch\f3\fs24\lang3081\sl276\slmult1\sb0\sa200{\afs22\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs22\lang9
- So (2) poses some interesting problems to which I feel should be addressed. Which is that, while vital metaphor can, in a particularly fluid way, give rise to the imagination of new metaphors created expressedly in order to describe some aspect of something that an existing language can't yet quite capture, and can induce a person to re-vitalize this conception (if it is 'dead' to them) and experience it as something that seemingly feels like what it might have been when it once was itself new and expressed originally[2], Vitalistic Imagination, and hence vital metaphor, is not itself strictly necessary to the creation or initial inception of a new metaphor, even if it creates a 'wholely new' concept. Someone may concieve of something newly that they do not experience in terms of vital metaphor, but which others do later on, for instance. So while newness of metaphor is heavily related to the vitality of metaphor, in that VI allows one to easily slip in to a mode of imagining where the metaphor is felt as if to be new and allows one to play with it in otherwise unfeesable ways (some of which are specifically discussed below in subsequent sections), someone with 'merely ordinary' (AKA non-vitalistic) modes of imagination can still freely compare likeness of things to other things to illustrate a point, and hence create new metaphors without VI (and hence VM) explicitly being involved, so long as the comparisons made don't force someone trying to comprehend them to use advanced features of VI that they are unable to access. As such, I understand the strongly felt intuition that metaphorical newness (in terms of expressive novelty) itself might be described and presented}{{\*\bkmkstart __DdeLink__8_702625238}\afs22\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs22\lang9
 such that it forms part of the essense of vital metaphor}{{\*\bkmkend __DdeLink__8_702625238}\afs22\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs22\lang9
[3].  }{\ul\ulc0\b\afs22\ab\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs22\lang9
Particularly}{\ul\ulc0\afs22\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs22\lang9
 when the novel metaphor genuinely does express something properly unexpressable in ordinary language}{\afs22\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs22\lang9
 my own 'essential' conception of vital metaphor does include this and doesn't differ from Stern's on these grounds as long as there really are aspects otherwise unexpressable. [CLARIFY THIS] However, if the expression, when it is concieved, does convey everything it needs to without using the special faculties of the SEC and VI, the sheer newness of the metaphorical expression doens't itself necessarily make it vital, at least possibly not immediately.[4] Due to this, I might permit Josef Stern's account of vital metaphor to potentially differ on this minor point (even though it is merely a typological description and not a definition), and I do so happily, while in mine I acknowledge that new metaphors can be coined/birthed, aged, developed and turned into the ashes forming a new 'literal' meaning, potentially without vital metaphor or imagination being involved, even though VI can breath further life into these metaphors beyond their conception[5], and may well be involved in their creation, especially if they are explicitly poetic. Yet, at the same time, I recognise the qualities described in this particular point as being things that }{\b\afs22\ab\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs22\lang9
do}{\afs22\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs22\lang9
 characterise vital metaphor when its workings are activly felt by the conscience, ultimately taking this as further evidence that the intuition behind Stern's VM shares the same source as my own.}
